# Magnetic Derivative Computation — `mag_rmi_bmc_compiled.tif`

## Background

`mag_rmi_bmc_compiled.tif` is the compiled Residual Magnetic Intensity (RMI) grid for the Bathurst Mining Camp. It lives in `data/raw/rasters/`. The existing pipeline reprojects raw rasters to EPSG:2953 at 100 m resolution (`reproject_grids.py`), then extracts point values for ML training. 

This plan adds a **new dedicated script** — `compute_mag_derivatives.py` — that computes standard geophysical derivatives directly on the **2D raster grid** (not the point sample table), saves each derivative as its own GeoTIFF in `data/processed/mag_derivatives/`, and makes them available as additional raster bands for `extract_features.py`.

---

## Proposed Derivatives

| # | Derivative | Symbol | Geophysical Purpose for VMS |
|---|------------|--------|------------------------------|
| 1 | **First Vertical Derivative** | FVD | Sharpens edges of magnetic bodies; highlights near-surface sources |
| 2 | **Total Horizontal Gradient** | THG | Delineates contacts/faults (ridges = boundaries of magnetic bodies) |
| 3 | **Analytic Signal Amplitude** | AS | Amplitude-only, position independent of inclination — useful at high latitudes |
| 4 | **Tilt Derivative** | TDR | Self-normalising; maps both strong and weak anomalies uniformly. Zero contour = body edge |
| 5 | **Tilt Horizontal Gradient** | THDR | Combines TDR + THG; sharper edge detection than either alone |
| 6 | **Second Vertical Derivative** | SVD | Enhances shallow, short-wavelength anomalies; suppresses regional field |

> **Why these derivatives?** VMS deposits are typically associated with:
> - **Faults/shear zones** → detected by THG and THDR zero-contours
> - **Near-surface mafic/felsic contacts** → FVD and AS
> - **Footprint alteration haloes** → TDR (uniform response regardless of body strength)
> - **Regional filtering** → SVD suppresses deep/broad signals to expose shallower targets

---

## Implementation Details

### Computation Approach
All derivatives are computed using **finite differences on the reprojected 100 m grid** (EPSG:2953). The RMI grid will first be reprojected (if not already done) before derivative computation.

**Derivative formulas:**
- `FVD` ≈ `∂B/∂z` computed in wavenumber domain (FFT-based — most accurate for potential field data)
- `THG = sqrt((∂B/∂x)² + (∂B/∂y)²)` via `np.gradient` on gridded data
- `AS = sqrt((∂B/∂x)² + (∂B/∂y)² + (∂B/∂z)²)` = `sqrt(THG² + FVD²)`
- `TDR = arctan(FVD / THG)`
- `THDR = sqrt((∂TDR/∂x)² + (∂TDR/∂y)²)`
- `SVD ≈ (∂/∂z)[FVD]` = second application of vertical derivative in wavenumber domain

### FFT-based vertical derivative
Using the **wavenumber domain** approach (multiply FFT by `|k| * 2π`) gives far better results than finite difference for the vertical derivative — this is the industry standard.

